8
00:00:36,600 --> 00:00:39,970
This is where children are operating using someone else&#39;s law.

9
00:00:39,970 --> 00:00:45,100
They&#39;re being guided by rewards and punishment rather than the morality of the issue.

10
00:00:45,100 --> 00:00:48,410
Their reasoning tends to be egocentric in the sense that they&#39;re mostly worried about

11
00:00:48,410 --> 00:00:53,039
what will happen to them, not about the fairness of the situation.

12
00:00:53,039 --> 00:00:56,930
When children hear a story like this one about Joe, children under the age of nine are likely

13
00:00:56,930 --> 00:01:01,010
to be categorized as having a preconventional morality level.

14
00:01:01,010 --> 00:01:05,450
In the first stage, they have an individual perspective on preconventional morality.

15
00:01:05,450 --> 00:01:07,930
They&#39;re focused on concrete tangibles.

16
00:01:07,930 --> 00:01:10,710
Their focus tends to be fairly egocentric.

17
00:01:10,710 --> 00:01:15,920
For stage two, children start to argue, Yes, “Joe shouldn&#39;t give the money because Joe

18
00:01:15,920 --> 00:01:20,640
can do whatever he wants with his money, and he wants to go to camp.&quot;

19
00:01:20,640 --> 00:01:25,770
Still egocentric, still worried just about a single person here, Joe, but now, they are

20
00:01:25,770 --> 00:01:30,399
thinking a little bit about fairness and what bigger systems this fits into, that he should

21
00:01:30,399 --> 00:01:32,450
be able to do what he wants with his money.

22
00:01:32,450 --> 00:01:33,450
Okay.

23
00:01:33,450 --> 00:01:37,969
Children reach the next level – Kohlberg’s conventional morality level - somewhere between

24
00:01:37,969 --> 00:01:39,479
